"Based on the retrieved social media posts, the following summary outlines the event regarding *Charlie Hebdo*, categorized by evidence strength:\n\n**Verified Facts**\n*   **Continuation of Publication:** High-trust verified sources confirm that *Charlie Hebdo* vowed to continue publishing following the incident, stating, \"The paper will continue because they didn’t win\" [2].\n*   **Global Solidarity with Nuance:** Verified sources indicate widespread support for *Charlie Hebdo* among journalists, specifically noting that most journalists in India stand with the publication. However, it is also verified that no Indian publication reprinted their most controversial work [4].\n\n**Informal but Genuine Observations**\n*   **Scope of Satire:** Unverified but plausible posts argue against the characterization that *Charlie Hebdo* was known specifically for mocking Muslims, asserting instead that the publication mocked \"everyone\" [5].\n\n**Unverified Rumours and Disputed Claims**\n*   **Inconsistencies in the Shooting:** There are claims from unverified sources suggesting \"inconsistencies\" regarding the shooting, though these are presented as nitpicking rather than established facts [3].\n*   **General Information:** One verified source links to general \"what we know so far\" content, but the specific details within those links are not provided in the text of the posts [1].\n\n**Conclusion**\nThe core verified fact is that *Charlie Hebdo* continued operations after the attack, supported by international journalistic solidarity, albeit with varying degrees of engagement (e.g., support without reprinting controversial content in India). Claims regarding specific inconsistencies in the shooting narrative remain unverified rumours."